Vodní plocha Kacabaji je využívaná jako přírodní koupaliště, najdeme tu upravené travnaté pláže. V areálu kolem vodní nádrže je hřiště na volejbal, minikopanou a sezónní stánek s občerstvením. Pod přehradní hrází je vybudováno parkoviště. Každoročně v letním období se u vodní nádrže koná soutěž nesoucí název O nejlepšího Valašského ptáka. Jihozápadním směrem se nachází oblast přírodní památky Prameny Zrzávky, kterou tvoří prameny vyvěrající nedaleko od sebe s rozdílným chemickým složením.

Plavecký bazén (25m) s mírně slanou vodou, jež na rozdíl od klasické sladkovodní chlorové technologie nezpůsobuje podráždění pokožky a sliznic. Vedle plaveckého bazénu je i dětské brouzdaliště. Vodní svět nabízí množství aqua atrakcí, jako např. divokou řeku, perličkovou masážní lavici, stěnovou hydromasáž, chrliče, vodní hřib, 40 m dlouhý tobogán (vstup pro děti od 10 let) či whirlpooly pro 6 a 12 osob. Vodní svět je propojen s plaveckým bazénem a voda je zde také mírně slaná. Parní lázeň pro relaxaci a uvolnění stresu, nachází se v prostorách plaveckého bazénu.

Rokytnický rybník je vcelku vhodným místem pro koupání nebo rychlé osvěžení pokud tudy projíždíte na kole. Kvalita vody je značně proměnlivá dle teploty a dalších okolností, které mohou způsobovat "kvetení vody". Vstup nebo skoky do vody usnadňuje renovovaná hráz u které jsou zároveň schůdky do vody. Kvalitu vody vynahradí nádherný výhled na zříceninu hradu Trosky a zároveň na druhé straně můžete vidět horu Kozákov, tedy obě dominanty Českého ráje z tohoto jediného místa. Menší "pláž" u hráze je travnatá a bývá vždy posekaná. Auto je možné zaparkovat v blízkosti hráze. Ze železniční stanice Borek je to přibližně 1800 m.

Menší zatopený kamenolom mezi obcemi Drysice a Želeč je v majetku obce Drysice, ale v nájmu ho mají potápěči z prostějovského klubu Krab, kteří by se o něj měli starat. Vstup do lomu je volný.

lupa
Vodní hladina je obklopena přibližně z jedné poloviny skalními stěnami vysokými 15 – 18 m. A právě skalní stěny zdejšího lomu se objevily v exteriérových záběrech několika českých celovečerních filmů, jako například Za humny je drak režiséra Radima Cvrčka z roku 1983 nebo Strašidla z vikýře stejného režiséra z roku 1988. V prostředí drysického lomu se natáčely i některé scény slovenského televizního seriálu pro děti Spadla z oblakov z roku 1978 režiséra Radima Cvrčka. Hlavní hrdinka Majka z Gurunu zde „chodila“ po vodní hladině zdejšího lomu. Naposledy se natáčelo v drysickém lomu na podzim roku 2010, kdy štáb Centra dramatické tvorby brněnského studia ČT zde natáčel některé sekvence nového televizního filmu Sejít z cesty s Jitkou Čvančarovou, Ondřejem Havelkou a Václavem Neužilem v hlavních rolích.

Vzniklo v l. 2005-6 jako malý štěrkopískový bagr poblíž Dubicka a Bohuslavic. Hlavní funkcí je poskytnout prostor pro šíření a uchování biotopů vodních živočichů i dalšího rostlinstva a živočichů v zemědělsky intenzivně využívané krajině. Okolí nádrže je osázeno dřevinami a poskytuje i místo k malým rekreačním aktivitám obyvatel blízkého okolí. Vodní plocha tak může i částečně nahrazovat tůně a slepá ramena, která kdysi v krajině určitě bývala před uzavření toku Moravy mezi ochranné hráze, které zamezily rozlévání vody do široké roviny v Mohelnické brázdě.

Plocha biocentra je 4,91ha, plocha vodní nádrže 1,46ha, průměrná hloubka 3,5m, maximální hloubka 7,5m, objem vody je 47000m3.

Díky štěrkopískům v naplavách Moravy zde najdeme čistou vodu, kdo si troufne, může si tu i zaplavat, ačkoliv to není žádné oficiální koupaliště, nikdo plavce nevyžene.

The Petites Chutes de la Lukaya is a set of small waterfalls on the Lukaya River. They are just south of Kinshasa, the capital city of the Democratic Republic of the Congo. They are perhaps 1 metre (3.3 ft) high. The low waterfalls empty into a small lake with a beautiful sandy beach. They are an attraction to tourists who come to swim or eat at the nearby restaurant. The Lola ya Bonobo sanctuary for endangered bonobos, which is just south of the falls, is also of interest to tourists.

Čistá voda, místa na skákání, na potápění do velkých hloubek koupaliště není ale potápět se tam ještě dá, jsou tam atrakce pro děti jako např. Skluzavka, vodní dělo, vodní tryska a dětský bazének. Velice relaxující je perličková koupel. Na každého člověka se tam mění 6 litrů vody. Pro nekoupající se, je tam okolo celého bazénu velká travnatá plocha třeba na opalování, a pro děti hřiště. Jelikož je mapa velice stará tak tam je jakási budova (Dnes je tam dobré koupaliště). Odpoledne je tam často hodně lidí, takže je lepší se jít koupat dopoledne. Bazén je nekrytý, venkovní.

Okolí jezera je romantické. Už jen samotný přístup k nádrži buď cestami a pěšinami vedoucími letitým lesem, nebo cestičkou vyšlapanou v trávě míjející starobylou chaloupku a studánku ve stínu staleté lípy srdčité (Tilia cordata) navodí v člověku tu správnou atmosféru, aby posléze žasl nad nevelkou vodní plochou částečně zarůstající přesličkou (Equisetum sp.) a orobincem (Typha sp.), lemovanou vzrostlým lesem s roztroušenými osamocenými balvany roztodivných tvarů.
Vlivem vodního prostředí a specifických klimatických podmínek se zde vytvořil jedinečný ekosystém se spoustou vodních i suchozemských druhů. Kdekoli na břehu svádí kouzlo místa posadit se a vnímat přírodu, která je všude kolem.

Východní část je vice chráněná před pohledy z venčí, možná i proto je striktně využívaná pouze naturisty. Západní část je textilní. Na svahu nad pláží je kolem cesty několik míst k parkování i možnost občerstvení v místních tavernách. Toalety na pláži nejsou. V naturistické části je vyústěná hadice s tekoucí sladkou vodou k osprchování.

Zatopená oblast po povrchové těžbě, písčitá pláž, přibývá vybavení jako převlékárny, sprchy, volejbalová hřiště, občerstvení, prolézačky atd. Do roku 2012 jedna z nejčistších vod v ČR, v současné době (2016) už zase krásně čisté, pokud nezvíříte písek, je vidět krásně až na dno. Zadní část občas obývají labutě, druhý rybník je chovný, resp. jsou (byly, naposledy jsme se tu koupali 2009) v něm ryby, lovit jsem jr ale nikdy nikoho neviděl. V roce 2009 vybudována online dráha s délkou asi 3,5 km. Nejlepší koupání je večer mezi 7-9 hodinou, kdy je hladina naprosto klidná, voda teplá a v okolí klid. Pokud se předtím ještě projedete na bruslích, tak parádní zážitek :-)

Bývalý povrchový lom začal být zavádění v roce 2005. V roce 2016 se zdá, že je již kompletně napuštený, ačkoli na několika místech stále v malém měřítku napouštění probíhá stále. Původní megalomanské ambice s tímto místem, jež si můžete prohlédnout na Habartovské vyhlídce, případně na internetu (kde je toho mnohem více) jsou oproti plánu z let 2005-2008 značně ve skluzu, otázkou je, kolik z toho a jestli se vůbec uskuteční (má zde jezdit parník, být tréninkové zázemí pro hasičský sbor, policii, přístav, několik pláží atd.). Lom je přístupný spíše ze strany od Svitavy, kde v několika posledních letech probíhala výstavba zátok, cest a úprava terénu. Z té je také působivý výhled na větrné elektrárny v Horním Cástkově a okolí. Při západu slunce jde o úžasnou podívanou. Že strany od Bukovan a Habartova je také pár použitelných přístupových míst do vody, ale vysloveně pláže zde nehledejte, stejně jako jakékoli zázemí.

column4: Complexo Aquático Caio Pompeu de Toledo
column14: Piscina pública para prática de natação, mergulho e lazer. Uso gratuíto para os moradores de São Paulo
V kempu Baldovec se nachází malý bazén.
O local conta com uma bela cachoeira para um banho refrescante. Também há trilhas e local ara piquenique.  A trilha da cachoeira tem 5.330 metros ida e volta que pode ser feito em até três horas
A Mata Atlântica mostra toda a sua beleza esse lugar maravilhoso. Há algus locais para se refrescar nos dias quentes. A atração principal é a cachoeira Véu de Noiva

A cachoeira do Jamil é uma das mais bonitas da confluência do rio Monos com o rio Capivari. Além da bela paisagem, na trilha até a cachoeira você encontra poços para tomar banho e outras quedas com águas cristalinas.
Ótimo espaço para banho, com uma pequena queda d'água para a criançada fazer a festa. A água é realmente cristalina.
Belo lugar para o pessoal da Zona Sul de São Paulo se refrescar. O acesso é super fácil e muitas pessoas aparecem por lá para se divertirem aos finais de semana.
Ótimo local para nadar e relaxar. A cachoeira fica dentro da Fazenda Maravilha e é bem fácil chegar até ela. A trilha de 1,2 km é rodeada por belezas naturais.

Essa é uma das mais charmosas e populares da serra do mar e fica a apenas 50 km de São Paulo. Para chegar até ela, é preciso percorrer uma trilha de aproximadamete 6 quilômtros. É um percurso de dificuldade moderada e não indicada para quem ão tem algum preparo físico.

Essa cachoeira é facilmente uma das mais bonitass de São Paulo, mas arachegar até ela é preciso percorrer uma trilha não muito fácil de cerca de 5km. Apesar de ter um poço na queda, o banho ali pode ser um pouco perigoso. De qualqer forma é um ótimo local para relaxar e estar contato com a natureza.

Além de linda, essa cachoeira é excelete para tomar um belo banho refrescante. Mas atenção: o acesso até ela é um pouco complicado. É preciso ter bom vigor físico e atenção para enfrentar as trilhas. Mas ao final, tudo terá valido à pena.

Quem acha que São Paulo não tem praia é porque ainda ao conhece o Parque Praia do Sol, às margens da Represa de Guarapiranga. Ótimo espaço para passar o dia com a família, curtir o sol e se refrescar com um bom banho de água doce. O parque fica aberto todos os dias das 7h00 às 19h00.
Super koupání na dlouhé písečné pláži. Spousta možnosti kurzu surfování a dalších plážových ptákovin.
Piscina pública para prática de natação, mergulho e lazer.
O complexo conta com uma piscina infantil e outra em formato de feijão. Além das piscinas, o local conta com uma linda e ampla área de lazer. Vale muito a visita.
O centro conta com duas piscinas para a prática de natação e lazer.
O clube cota com uma piscina infantil para lazer e outra semiolímpica para a prática de natação.

Um dos lugares mais boitos de São Paulo para um bom banho de piscina. O espaço é amplo e conta com muito verde. O único problema é que nos finais de semana de calor, parece que todos os moradores de São Paulo vão para lá.

Se você gosta de se divertir a água, isso é tudo o que precisa. O Sesc Itaquera conta com parque aquático que possui um espelho d’água de 5.000 metros quadrados, cinco piscinas recreativas, cascatas, chafarizes, correntezas e oito pistas de toboágua.
Espaço cota com três piscinas aquecidas, sendo que uma delas é semiolímpica. Além disso, também há uma área para banho de sol. Ótimas istalações em um endereço privilegiado.
Essa unidade do Sesc possui três piscinas cobertas e aquecidas: uma semi-olímpica, uma recreativa e uma infantil.
Com uma piscina semiolímpica aquecida, a unidade oferece atividades de recreação e treino de natação. Belas e modernas instalações.
Você provavelmente nunca viu uma piscina tão grade quanto essa. É uma das maiores da América Latina, podendo comportar até três mil banhistas ao mesmo tempo.
O complexo aquático conta com três piscinas para lazer e a prátca de natação. Localizado no Parque Ecológico do Tiête, o local conta com natureza exuberante, apesar das águas poluídas do rio Tietê.

Essa pedreira é um templo para os mergulhadores de São Paulo. Ela conta com dois lagos: um de 36 metros de profundidade e a outra com cerca de 75. É preciso cuidado para se aveturar aqui, já que não são raros os casos de mortes de mergulhadores a localidade.

Localizado na costa de São Sebastião, litoral norte de São Paulo, o Arquipélago de Alcatrazes é um dos locais procurados para se mergulhar no estado de SP.
A visibilidade pode alcançar os 20m no verão, permitindo um visibilidade de até 20 metros ao mergulhador. O local também é muito bem preservado, exibindo uma grande variedade de fauna e flora.
A ilha é, a verdade, um parque de preservação ambiental, com praias e locais para mergulho.

Localizada na represa Nova Avanhadava, é até difícil acreditar que as águas dalí são as mesmas que cortam o rio Tietê na altura da capital paulista. Tudo muito limpo e lindo. Vale muito curtir o dia de sol aqui.
Localizada na margem oeste do Ribeirão da Fartura, essa prainha é ótima para tomar um banho em um belo dia de sol.
Localizada na margem leste do Ribeirão da Fartura, a prainha é perfeita para curtir um dia de sol com amigos e familiares. Diversão garantida.
Localizada as margens do Rio Cubatão, essa prainha é o orgulho da região de Medonça.
Essa é quase uma ilha paradisíaca banhada pelas águas da Represa Água Vermelha. Local conta com chalés, quiosques, camping e lanchonete. Tudo o que você precisa para curtir um dia de sol.
A Praia Pôr-do-Sol cota com 328 metros de extesão, águas límpidas e um visual deslumbrate. É uma das maravilhas de Pereira Barreto.
Ótimo local para se refrescar e tomar banho de sol.

Největší aqupark v Evropě. Určený pro celou rodinu. Najdete zde všechno od relaxace v saunách a SPA až po bláznivé zážitky z 26 různých tobogánů a skluzavek. Aqupark má vnitřní i venkovní část, z nichž některé se mohou i zaměňovat díky otevírajícím se střechám.
Se você quer um lugar agradável para matar esse calor que está te matado, essa prainha e para você. Só tome cuidado, porque alguns pontos do rio são perigosos.
A menos de 30 minutos São Paulo, dentro da Reserva Florestal do Morro Grande, você encontra a bela queda d'água formada pelos rios da Graça e Cotia.
Essa é a cachoeira mais conhecida das trilhas de Paranapiacaba. Além da queda principal, existem outras menores para os visitantes aproveitarem.

Essa cachoeira fica entre os municípios de Embu Guaçu e Itanhaém. A trilha para chegar até ela é de aproximadamente três horas e demanda muita ateção, já que é cheia de bifurcações. A melhor coisa é ir acompanhado de um guia local.

Não é fácil chegar até essa cachoeira. São 9 quilômetros de trilhas no meio da Mata Atlântica. Mas as belezas naturais compensam o esforço. Sem contar que a Cachoeira da Usina é certamente uma das mais boitas de São Paulo.
Pěkná velká protipovodňová nádrž vhodná ke koupání, udržované okolí. Přístup do vody z travnatých břehů, velké plochy na ležení.

Splav v městské částí Poušov na řece Jihlavě.
Vhodné ke koupání a blbnutí, hlavně v létě, ale občas zavítá i polární medvěd. Občerstvení v docházkové vzdálenosti v kempu.

O Parque Ecologico Gustavo Simioni, mais conhecinho como a prainha de Sertãozinho, é ideal para quem quer curtir um dia agradável em meio à natureza. Há várias opções de lazer no local. Vale muito a pena.
Ótimo local para curtir um dia de sol com familiares e amigos. As água da represa do Broa são bem clarinhas e a região de Itirapina é de uma beleza atural ímpar.
Lugar perfeito para o lazer com a família e ou amigos. Muitos pontos com areia para banho de sol.
Essa é uma ótima opção de lazer para os moradores de toda a região. Muito boa infraestrutura, com salva-vidas, água potável e energia disponíveis.
Ótimo local para curtir com familiares e amigos. O local conta com infraestrutura completa, chuveiros, quiosques, campings e estacionamento.

column4: Balneário Municipal Águas de Santa Bárbara
column14: Balneário com banhos de imersão em banheira, ofurô, saunas seca e úmida, duchas circular e escocesa.

column4: Balneário Municipal de Águas de Lindóia
column14: O Balneário Edison Brasil Tozzi Rizzo, oferece mais de 30 serviços entre banhos de imersão, massagens, piscinas de água mineral, ducha escocesa, banho de argila, tudo isso em um espaço agradabilíssimo, cercado de verde e belos jardins projetados pelo paisagista Burle Marx.
Essa é quase uma ilha paradisíaca banhada pelas águas da Represa Água Vermelha.

column4: Thermas Water Park de São Pedro
column14: Com 11 piscinas, o parque oferece atrações para todas as idades. Três delas contam com águas quentes, mas também há o parque aquático infantil, toboáguas, queda livre de 10 metros etc.

O Thermas dos Laranjais é um prues aquáticos mais visitados em todo o mudo. Conta com toboáguas, pista de surfe, piscina de ressurgência, piscinas de sonolências, rio lento de corredeira e parque infantil.
O Thermas Antonio Carlos oferece serviços como: hidrologia, banhos, duchas, saunas, mecanoterapias.
Mesmo sob domínio de hotéis, as banheiras e piscinas de águas termais ficam abertas a todo o público.
Resorts com piscinas naturais, praias artificiais e parque de águas quentes são as grandes atrações de uma das maiores estâncias hidrotermais do mundo.
O Hot Park é um dos únicos parque aquático de águas naturalmente quentes do mundo.

O Parque das Fontes conta com oito piscinas de águas quentes naturais, abertas 24 horas por dia. Ao todo, o local conta com 18 nascentes, sendo o maior conjunto de águas quentes correntes naturais do mundo.
Bela lagoa de águas termais transparentes e cheia de peixes e algas. Parece mais um aquário natural!

O parque tem piscinas termais, toboágua, rio da preguiça, bar molhado etc. Dizem que suas águas, cujas temperaturas que variam de 31 a 43 graus, são de grande valor terapêutico, com poder de diminuir a viscosidade do sangue, aumentar a vitalidade sexual, melhorar a digestão gástrica e duodenal, e também contribuindo para a fisioterapia.
No Balneário de Águas Termais, os visitantes econtram um ambiente arborizado, águas cristalinas e quentes , toboáguas, rampa molhada, piscinas infantis etc. Ótima infraestrutra.

O Complexo Hidrotermal conta com sete piscinas de águas termais, que vertem a 41°C de uma profundidade de 700 metros de profundidade. Os visitantes também podem entrar com as belezas naturais da região e até mergulhar no Rio da Prata.
O parque conta com diversas piscinas de águas termais, banhos de imersão, duchas e tratamentos medicinais. Há também um chafariz natural, que lança a água a 30 metros de altura.
O resort fica próximo às cataratas e conta com 192 mil m² de área, onde os visitantes encontram piscinas e praia de águas termais.
O resort conta com parque aquático, onde se encontram as piscinas de águas termais naturais, piscinas de água fria cobertas e ao ar livre.

Super osvěžení při pěší nebo cyklistické túře Slavkovským lesem. Krásné tiché a romantické místo s "kanadskou" atmosférou. Na auto zde úplně zapomeňte, sem se musí pouze pěšky nebo na kole. A hajný Jedlička se tu opravdu s nikým nepáře! Nejbližší parkování je na vjezdu do lesa u krásenského koupaliště - asi 2km.

Dovolte nám představit nově vznikající a ve všech ohledech jedinečnou lokalitu Wake Park Náklo, která se pyšní průzračně čistou vodou a nachází se jen 15 min od Olomouce. V areálu Wake Park Náklo jsme pro Vás vybudovali vodní vlek Wakemaster 2.0 určený pro nadšence wakeboardingu a vodního lyžování. Na nově vzniklých písčitých plážích se budete cítit jako u moře. Dále je Vám k dispozici půjčovna paddleboardů, wake vybavení a neoprenů, dále pak multifunkční hřiště na beach volejbal a další sportovní aktivity. V našem Wake baru Vám nabídneme domácí limonády, spoustu alko-nealkoholických nápojů a koktejlů, rychlé občerstvení, gril a spoustu dalších dobrot od naší usměvavé obsluhy. Věříme, že návštěva našeho areálu ve Vás zanechá ty nejhezčí vzpomínky a zážitky.

The Blue Lagoon (Icelandic: Bláa lónið) is a geothermal spa in southwestern Iceland. The spa is located in a lava field near Grindavík on the Reykjanes Peninsula, in a location favourable for geothermal power, and is supplied by water used in the nearby Svartsengi geothermal power station. (source: Wikipedia)

Mývatn Nature Baths, ☎ +354-464-4411 (info@jardbodin.is, fax: +354-464-4422), [1]. Summertime: 09:00 – 24:00, Wintertime: 12:00 – 22:00. Something of a "Blue Lagoon lite", the Mývatn Nature Baths was opened in June 2004 and offers mineral-rich geothermal waters drawn from depths of up to 2500 meters. Facilities include a reception area and cafeteria, changing rooms and showers, three natural steam baths accommodating up to 50 bathers at a time, and a 5000m2 geothermal bathing pool maintained at a constant temperature of 38-40ºC. 2500 ISK.

This rustic pool was opened in 1891 and used until 1937 before being abandoned for over 60 years. It is the oldest swimming pool in Iceland and has been renovated in recent years. This beautiful lagoon has become increasingly popular and is only a short detour from the famous Golden Circle Route.
Easily accessible on the Golden Circle Route on the way to Gullfoss Waterfall, this sleek lake-front spa is well worth a visit for its pool, three hot tubs and sauna. (source: heyiceland.is)

Seljavallalaug is among the oldest swimming pools in Iceland, built in 1923. The pool is nestled in a valley beneath the infamous Eyjafjallajökull Glacier, not far from Skógafoss Waterfall. The pool is very picturesque and makes a very interesting stop along the South Coast. (source: heyiceland.is)

Experience nature from its core by bathing in the lovely Krauma bath. The hot water originates in Europe's most powerful hot spring, Deildartunguhver, at a temperature of 100°C (212°F). To achieve the perfect bathing temperature they mix the boiling hot water with glacial water from Rauðagil Canyon. Here you find relaxing natural geothermal baths, a cold tub to get your blood circulation going, two calming saunas, and a relaxation room where you can rest by the fireplace while listening to soothing music. (heyiceland.is)

The Blue Lagoon is the most famous pool in Iceland and one of the most popular Iceland attractions. It has been named as one of the 25 wonders of the world according to National Geographic and an absolute must-see on your trip to Iceland. The milky blue waters and the white silica mud make the lagoon a unique one. (heyiceland.is)
This is Iceland's largest and most visited swimming pool complex with Olympic size lap pools and hot tubs of various kinds and sizes. This pool has something for everyone. (source: heyiceland.is)

Víti('Hell') is one of the most interesting natural wonders in Iceland. It is a explosion crater which contains a geothermal lake of opaque blue, mineral-rich, warm water. Although the name isn't particularly inviting, many visitors like to take a dip in the lake. (source: heyiceland.is)

This is a very well-hidden secret that offers such an amazing and bizarre experience. In fact, Heydalur is so off-the-beaten-track that your GPS will probably tell you that it is not even possible to get there. Don't worry - it lies! When you get here you will see that there are actually three pools to choose from: one small indoor pool, a man-made rocky pool and a tiny natural hot spring. And why is this experience bizarre? - You ask. Well... because here you can swim in a greenhouse with grape vines and fruit trees growing all around you after eating said fruit at the Heydalur restaurant. (heyiceland.is)

Arguably the most beautiful swimming pool in the country - and with the best view! - the Hofsos pool is located on a hillside by the fjord of Skagafjordur. It gives a great view over the fjord and its islands, notably Drangey, Malmey, as well as the Thordarhofdi peninsula and the mountains on the other side of the fjord, all adding up to a stunning scenery.
Come rain or shine, the vista from the pool is a combination of marvellous different shades of blue; the clear blue colour of the swimming pool itself, the green-blue sea, the dark blue of the islands and mountains in the distance, and finally the blueness of the sky on a clear day. The size of the pool is 25x10.5 m and you‘ll have a hot tub to soak in, as well as a steam bath and an infrared sauna.
The architecture of both the pool and the surrounding facilities is exemplary, attracting people from all over. (guidetoiceland.is)

For centuries, the geothermal heat north of Húsavík has been known to residents, who have utilized it for bathing and washing. Drilling for hot water at Húsavíkurhöfði in the mid-20th century revealed water that turned out to be hot seawater, too rich in minerals to be suitable for heating houses.
Instead of letting this hot water go to waste, an old cheese barrel was installed at Húsavíkurhöfði. There, Húsavík residents could enjoy the health benefits of bathing in hot seawater. Those suffering from skin conditions such as psoriasis have found relief by bathing in the water, which is at an optimal temperature of 38°-39°C.
The water in the GeoSea sea baths comes from two drillholes, one located by the cheese barrel and the other by Húsavík harbor. There is no need to use any cleaning agents or equipment, as the steady flow of water from the drillholes, between the pools, over their edges and into the sea ensures that the water stays within the limits stipulated by health regulations.
The GeoSea sea baths enable you to enjoy nature in a unique manner. Thanks to the underground heat, the seawater in the baths is warm and comfortable and the mineral-rich water will caress your skin. While the warm sea works its miracles, you can enjoy the view of the mountain range to the west, Skjálfandi Bay beneath the cliffs and the Arctic Circle itself on the horizon. Source: https://www.geosea.is/en/about-us/geosea

After 16 km, there is a "Lunski Maslinici"" sign on the road and a map of the ""Olive Trees of Lun"" Nature Trail. You can take a walk from this place according to the educational trail on the roadside. The pedestrian way leads alternately in the shadow of the cultivated olive trees, which, due to climatic conditions on the island, are twisted into bizarre shapes. Most trees are about 400 years old. You will also find here trees still growing for over 850 years. The oldest the olive tree was estimated to be planted more than 1150 years ago."
350 permanent residents who already in the past lived from growing and processing olive fruits, fishing, goat and sheep farming

After 2 km from the village of Lun, turn right to the village of Mulobedanj. After almost reaching the sea you can park in a small parking lot on the left of the road. The parking is a part of a smaller restaurant called "Crnika"", where you can order food and sit in the shade of local oaks, right by the seashore and small sandy beaches suitable for children."
Pag cheese production
The mud is suitable for the treatment of rheumatic and dermatological diseases. Apply to the sick place and let it dry and stiffen. After an hour or two, the mud is washed or flushed in the sea.

Very few visitors to the island of Pag know that there is an Ornithological Reserve called Kolansko blato. Mainly in spring, freshwater lakes and marshes are created here, using waterfowl and many amphibians. In Kolansko, the mud can be reached by a marked turning to the road connecting Novalja and Kolan.
Excellent grilled squids will be preparer for you on the city promenade in the Dubrava restaurant.

This spring-fed quarry lake is the perfect suntrap. The beautiful jade water glistens within a rocky amphitheatre and there are flat ledges for jumping and grassy areas for picnics and sunbathing. It's a beautiful walk out on to the moor past the Hurlers – one of the most complete remains of a stone circle in the south-west. From the Hurlers car park in Minions, follow the track, which heads north on to the moor; walk past the circle and after 15 minutes bear left at the junction. You can return via the Pony Pool and the "Cheese Ring" tor: a stack of weathered rocks piled up like lumps of mozzarella.

At Totnes jump on a restored steam train that runs on the South Devon Railway for the three-mile trip up the line to Staverton village. You'll find a gentle and relatively warm stretch of the river Dart – deep and still above the weir and more secluded, with little beaches, downstream. Follow the path downstream from the station for 20 minutes, beyond the weir, and you'll come to a superb jump on a corner bend, with steps built up the trunk of an old oak tree that overhangs the pool. It's an exhilarating plunge into the dark, peaty water below. Return via the Sea Trout Inn and back up along the lane.

This is one of the best wild swims within easy reach of London. Get off the train at Pangbourne and head upstream three miles via the ancient oaks of Coombe Park. You're right on the edge of the Chilterns here and you'll find a wonderful wild stretch of river with chalky banks, clear water – and not a building in sight. Continue for another three miles to the pretty pubs in Goring-on-Thames, then jump on the train home. Alternatively walk or swim downstream from Pangbourne – it's six miles back to Reading – taking in the meadows with views of the historic Mapledurham house.

The Waveney was the favourite river of Roger Deakin – forefather of the wild swimming movement. I love the two-mile loop around Outney Common, starting and returning from Bungay. This town is one of Suffolk's most independent little places, with quirky cafes, craft stores and antiques dealers, and it has its own river meadows at the bottom of Bridge Street, perfect for a picnic and a quick dip. There's also Outney Meadow Caravan Park, a riverside campsite with canoe hire. It's a good river for spotting otters too, though you'll need to wait until nightfall. Head out under a full moon and embark on a lunar snorkel safari.

The Lugg is one of several idyllic rivers that rise in Wales and flow down through England along the Welsh Marches. At Bodenham you are spoilt for choice, with long sandy beaches and river pools [see footnote]. Follow the path behind the church and cross the bridge to find the beaches downstream. Afterwards head for the village of Hope Under Dinmore, a mile to the north on the Marches Way, and visit the superb castle and gardens of Hampton Court. For picnic supplies, the yummy Monkland Cheese Dairy is excellent for replacing any fat you burned off during your swim.

column4: River Trent, Anchor Church, Ingleby, Derbyshire
column9: The great river Trent doesn't sound promising, but there are plenty of bucolic stretches to explore. Extraordinary caves of Anchor Church, a mile upstream from Ingleby near Derby, where the river has carved out a series of rock grottos. Hermits and saints have inhabited this remote place since the sixth century, adding windows and fireplaces. The swimming, in a quiet lagoon just off the river, is safe and it's a perfect place to explore with children or to shelter from the rain.

Fordwich is thought by some to be England's smallest town. Set off from the old town hall and follow the path downstream along the Stour. The river is at first open and sunny, but becomes wooded and secretive after two miles, before winding through the reedy lowlands of the Stodmarsh nature reserve, good for spotting bittern, marsh harriers and water vole. You can only reach this section by swimming or canoeing, and if you continue through you'll eventually arrive at the Grove Ferry Inn in Upstreet.

Ullswater is one of the most popular and beautiful lakes in the Lake District, but to escape the crowds head for this high, gnarly crag. There are twisted oaks and rowan trees, and a brilliant jump from the crag into deep, clear water. With its west-facing aspect it's a perfect place for swimming at sunset, and there's a beach alongside where you can brew up and make supper. Take the ferry to Howtown pier and follow the lake path a mile south-west; or take the Howtown turning from Pooley Bridge. You'll pass several beaches en route and Park Foot camping has lakeshore pitches.

column4: Lower Ddwli Falls, Waterfall Woods, Brecon Beacons
column9: In the south-west hills of the Brecon Beacons, near Ystradfellte, you'll find some of the most amazing waterfall plunge pools in Britain. There are more than 20 pools along five miles of the Fechan and Mellte rivers, so you could try dipping in every one of them on a long day's walk. Lower Ddwli Falls is my favourite, a huge open pool with a great arc of a waterfall. Spray lifts up through the leaves and on a sunny day there are rainbows everywhere. Just downstream is Horseshoe Falls, with a great jump and rope swing. To reach them walk up the forest path from Pontneddfechan's Angel Inn or park at Pont Melinfach car park, off the Ystradfellte road, and walk downstream. If you want to make a weekend of it stay at Clyngwyn Bunkhouse.

There are thousands of lochs in Scotland, and open access laws mean you can swim in virtually all of them. One of my favourites is Loch Caoldair, on the western edge of the Cairngorms. It's only a mile from the road (three and a half miles south of Laggan) but it's completely wild and hidden among birch woods, with a lovely little beach. Afterwards, refuel with homely food and a warm welcome at the remote Monarch Hotel in Laggan and admire the ruined church. There are some great waterfalls a mile down the road at Strathmashie Forest, with a perfect place to pitch your tent right by the edge of the water, ready for that early morning skinny dip.

Both thrill seekers and swimmers will enjoy a splash in the Blue Lagoon in Abereiddy, Pembrokeshire. Grey slate gives the breached 25m-deep quarry pool a brilliant blue colour. The remains of the old quarry building also make great platforms to jump from. We love it so much that we even held a round of the Red Bull Cliff Diving series there back in 2013.

The Marine Conservation Society Good Beach Guide recommended Treyarnon Beach in 2014, praising its excellent water quality – and who are we to argue with them? But it’s not just the beach that’s worth coming for. Check out that tidal rock pool! Take care at high tide, though, as the pools become dangerous when waves can come crashing over the sides. From mid to high tide the beach is also popular with surfers – but watch out for rips!

column4: Llyn y Fan Fach, Brecon Beacons, Wales
column9: Those easily spooked might want to give Llyn y Fan Fach in the Brecon Beacons a miss – supposedly it’s one of the most haunted bodies of water in Wales! Local legend says that at 2pm on the first Sunday in August, the ‘Lady of the Lake’ – rumoured to be a woman killed by her violent husband – emerges from the water. Hmmm...we’re thinking: Sunday in August in Wales – it’s probably just the dayglow white body of one of the local swimmers!

Go swimming with a moorhen or two in Somerset’s River Frome. Join the Farleigh and District Swimming Club and enter a proud tradition of wild swimming that dates back to the 1930s. They operate a payment system: £1 for adults and 50p for kids.

Catch a wave or soak up the sun on this two-mile stretch of white sand in County Londonderry on the north coast of Northern Ireland, named one of the UK’s best beaches by Rough Guides. If you tire of swimming, it’s also a National Trust conservation site so you can check out the butterflies and wild pansy flowers, if you dig that sort of thing. Or for something a bit different try your hand at slacklining.

What’s not to love about a 60ft chute of water? A “bottomless” plunge pool beneath is also great for anyone who wants to dive or jump from a 6ft high ledge. Find it: Turn off the A697 at the junction to Ingram. Follow the valley road and park before starting the walk at Hartside Farm. Start the walk at O.S Grid Reference: NT 976 163.
Aquapark

Uzasny termalni park pro vsechny vekove kategorie. Kemp+vstup akvapark+polopenze 30E, deti zdarma.
Neusiedlersee-ne prave nejcistsi, ale krasne misto k nocovani. Pristav, hriste pro deti.

Hezky termalni akvapark s prirodni scenerii. Mnoho mist krytych pred sluncem, rozsahla vnitrni lecebna cast s opravdu vyraznou vodou. Caste animace pro deti. Festival jidla v obci v puli cervence stoji za navstevu.
Koupaliště je necelý 1km od Počátek, čistá voda.

column4: West Beach, Berneray, Isles of Harris
column9: The clear turquoise waters of Berneray are reached by wandering through dunes and crossing fine, white sands. The island’s colourful landscape is covered in stone circles. With exquisite views, it is perhaps the most beautiful swimming beach in the UK; brace yourself for the cold waters!

At the head of a wild glen a tall, slender waterfall falls into a high basin, flows through a circular hole and drops into a plunge pool (the kieve). This is a holy place with prayer flags, a shrine room above and lots of steps. There is a small tea room in the hermitage. An entrance fee applies.

There are a series of pools and falls on Cwm Llan at the bottom of the Watkins path and the waterfall is popular with walkers eager to freshen up after climbing Mount Snowdon.

From Beddgelert (A498), continue past Llyn Dinas and park beyond Gwynant Chapel café (LL55 4NL) on the right. Explorers can continue to the secluded pools on the nearby Afon Merch (53.0520,-4.0399). Llanberis waterfalls (53.1115, -4.1255) are also worth a visit on the north side of Snowdon (20 minutes, 53.0441, -4.0551).
A graceful column of water falls 10 metres into a deep, large plunge pool. Set in a wooded amphitheatre, you can also climb behind the fall and dive back in.
Galleny Force has two sets of pools and cascades, with grassy knolls and ancient rowan trees, fun for plunging, snorkelling and picnics.
A series of pools and deep pots for a half mile above the well-known Aira Force waterfall.
A huge waterfall with pool on a wild moor.

Here you'll find two spectacular waterfalls set deep in a woody gorge. One is five metres high with an 80m-wide plunge pool, open and awe-inspiring. The other is 12 metres high with a 50m-wide plunge pool.

A wide waterfall, about three metres high, with a pleasant plunge pool and an open aspect by the roadside. There are limestone cliffs in the valley and grassy banks for picnics, as well as interesting river and rock shapes downstream and good paddling.
An atmospheric waterfall set in woodland on the edge of a moor with a small pool beneath towering rocks.
A lovely little clear plunge pool with a cave. Perfect for families.
A famous waterfall with an overhang and a large pool popular with bathers.
Eas Chia-aig is a series of three falls and pools set in quick succession by the roadside with interesting rock formations.

A deep, large, black plunge pool (30 metres) at the base of Scotland’s second highest waterfall. The remains of Victorian viewing gangways can still be found around the pool and it can be a tricky scramble down into this forested canyon.
There are impressive pools by these roadside falls. The lane continues along the wild shores of Tummel and Rannock lochs (B846).
Deep large pools and waterfalls with clear water flow through this truly wild river valley.

A very pleasant 25 minute walk south along the tops of the cliffs from Heartland Quay gets you to Speke's Mill Mouth waterfall. Waterfall with a medium depth pool, this one is on a beautiful stretch of rugged Devon coastline.
These beautiful twin lakes are perfect for swimming.

This heart-shaped lake halfway up Snowdon is the perfect swimming spot for lovers. Even more romantic, Welsh folklore has it that this was where King Arthur had Bedivere throw Excalibur and where Arthur's body was later placed in a boat to be carried away to Avalon.
This is outdoor-swimming heaven, with invigorating temperatures and gobsmacking views.

This is where wild swimming gets really WILD, with plenty of sky-high jumping spots -the more casual bather may want to swerve this one. For those diving in, you can expect to swim alongside wild salmon, which may make you feel rather cumbersome, especially when they leap in and out of the water.

Home to the infamous Serpentine Swimming Club, which meets every morning (and has done so for the past 150 years), this swimming spot is as civilised as wild swimming gets. Every Saturday morning at 8am, club members gather for the weekly race, and wetsuits are BANNED. Non-members can take the plunge from May to September only.
Vstupné 4€
Přístup je krkolomější, ale voda průzračná. Dá se skákat ze skály
wakeboard. Koupání i se psem.

“Most people have to pay to go on a boat tour to see the iconic Chenonceaux Abbey and châteaux. So to be able to swim down, through and under this incredible châteaux is not only like swimming through French history, but it also feels a bit illicit. Like you’re getting something for free. It’s a stunning backdrop, especially at sunset." source: https://www.redbull.com/gb-en/best-wild-swimming-spots-france
beautiful beach by the norh sea
Amrum

This curvy stretch of babbling water is so pretty Lewis Carroll apparently drew inspiration from it for Alice's Adventures in Wonderland. You'll float past little beaches and grassy meadows filled with cattle. Just watch out for boats.

If you're not too afraid of Nessie, wild swimming in Britain's longest lake is a wee must for the bucket list. Experts recommend starting from the small beach opposite Urquhart Castle and wading down through the fields. Hopefully it'll just be the cold that nips...

Did you love Jurassic Park? You should visit Burton Bradstock, with its honey-coloured, crumbling cliffs and fossils from the ancient Jurassic Coast. Slip in from the pebbly Hive beach and make your way down the twinkly blue expanse.

Jump into Llyn Cau, the melted glacier slap-bang in the middle of the crater of Cadair Idris, that's what. The 1,150ft ascent will have you gagging for a chilling dip, even if you're surrounded by freshly fallen snow.
One of the best beaches in Poland. No trash, no jellyfish, only nice sand. Be careful, there are kitesurfers.
Nice beach with many services.
Wide beach on the east border of Poland. Not so much occupied as the one in Triple City.
What a lovely place. The cafe culture. the ambiance is lovely. A great place to take the family. I wish I had visited sooner. Another place on my bucket list to go back to.

We visited a few times, every time via a different entrance, our favorite number 23, on the eastern side of the Piasnica delta. We found especially the walks from 23 eastwards, and then having a drink or some food in the Kontener Dębki, quite pleasant; or else a walk in Dębki center followed by a bite in Dębki Playa. The beach is quite clean, except maybe around the popular entrances, like next to the Kontener Dębki.
Poměrně čistá voda a (velice) pozvolný vstup

The beach is without a doubt Kolobrzeg's main attraction. The sand is fine and comfy, the beach is wide and long, the water is clear and inviting, the wooden breakwaters offer a place to roosting sea birds and make for charming pictures. A bit eastward one finds classic 30s/40s beach chairs for rent, charming.
The New Danube, however, contains numerous grassy hideaways along the banks, meaning that you can get as close or as far away from the company as you please. Nice place for swimming
The southernmost bathing lake in Austria, Faaker See is a haven in the summer, with blissful turquoise waters and an expanse of jagged mountains in the background – it is totally picture perfect.

Very beautiful lake with many activities nearby. Food, hiking, swimming, coffee.

Located in the charming and popular holiday town of Gmunden in Upper Austria, this beautiful and gigantic lake is renowned for its pure waters, making it perfect for impromptu summer dips.

The Erlaufsee is hugged by sandy beaches and is blessed with spectacular surroundings. As well as swimming, diving, surfing, boating, and fishing also take place on these stunning waters. Located between Styria and Lower Austria, there are many holiday homes available to rent nearby.

The Wörthersee lives in a southern area of Austrian known as the state of Carinthia. The popular bathing lake is a lively tourist destination in summertime, not only popular with swimmers, but with a variety of water sports enthusiasts too.

Achensee is the largest lake in Tyrol, and certainly one of the most beautiful beautiful too. The sandy beaches attract many sun worshippers and the incredible clear waters make it a popular destination for diving.
Weisssee is primarily known for being a popular skiing resort, but in the summertime it doubles up as a fantastic swimming location. Very cold and clean water.

Bath warm, transparent water and dreamy mountain backdrops are just a few of the drawing points of this lake in mid Carinthia. Temperatures average around 27 degrees in the summer, and the shallow lakeside makes it perfect for quick dips or lengthy swims.

Over 9,000 square metres of the best quality water entice swimmers all summer long at this lake in Styria. A 70-metre long water slide as well as a beach bar, and restaurant make it perfect for families.
The beaches along Hamburg's Elbe River are known as the Elbstrand
Binz is the most beautiful beach in the island of Rügen
Ahlbeck Beach makes for the quintessential German summer escape.
Berlin boasts many lakes including the Schlachtensee, positioned in the southwestern section of the city.
Beautiful, clean and privat lake. Nice stroll around the lake (2 hours). There are some private and public beaches as well. Swimming is allowed, but no boats or scuba driving.
Perfect for swimming, very nice water temperature. Very peaceful place to relax. Absolutely silent in non summer season . Easy to walk around and hiking trails around there are very easy to walk.
Nice swimming lake.

The lake is a mountain lake located at Zugspitze, the highest mountain of Germany. Therefore the water is refreshing but luckily not too cold. There are plenty of things to do at this lake: sipping a coffee at the terrace located directly at the lake, walking around the lake (which is around 8 kilometres), renting a boat or a SUP or hiking in the area. But also just having a swim there and tan is very pleasant.
One of the best lakes to swim in Munich is Walchensee. This one became my second favourite just last weekend because the water is sometimes even more clear and turquoise than of Lake Eibsee.

The good thing about Lake Wörthsee is that it is reachable by S-Bahn from Munich and it is not as popular and busy as for example Starnberger See or Tegernsee. However, it is not a very special lake either. But there are some beautiful spots and you can also rent SUPs or boats there.

This lake is well-known, sometimes a bit posh and the one populated the most with the most infrastructure around the like (compared to Lake Walchensee and Eibsee where is almost no infrastructure around the lake). However, Tegernsee is attractive for other reasons: the charming villages, the restaurants located at the lake, the hiking or MTB options in the area, but also for the swimming. If you prefer having a Spritz at a pretty terrace than actually jumping in the lake, then this is your place to go. You might even feel like at Lake Garda in Italy.
In summer, the lake is a great place to rest, as there are four swimming areas where you can refresh yourself on hot days in the cool waters.

The largest lake in Eastern Bavaria is perfect for swimming but also for water-skiing or surfing!

The best place for bathing at Lake Steinberg features a large sunbathing area and is located on its eastern bank, between the water rescue building and the Seetreff Müller boat rental.

Made from a former brown coal pit, it is one of the main attractions for swimmers and water sports enthusiasts.

Bathing, surfing, large swimming area with sand beach, beautiful, natural bays, sunbathing lawns, beach volleyball field, table tennis, playground, outdoor stage with various events and concerts, kiosk, bathroom facilities, changing rooms, Mediterranean restaurant with a beautiful sun terrace and an ADAC-award-winning campground located directly on the lake.

The forest lakes in Wiesau are former clay pits that could not be drained. One of the lakes, the so-called “Kipp,” was turned into a swimming lake. A pier, an island and a children’s pool offer lots of swimming fun. A kiosk, restrooms, changing rooms and showers are also available.

Bazén má rozměry 21x10 metrů, hloubka je 40-140 cm. Voda je díky menším rozměrům bazénu a hloubce poměrně teplá: 25-26 stupňů. V areálu je dětské hřiště s atrakcemi, víceúčelové hřiště pro míčové hry, k dispozici je občerstvení. Vstup do areálu a koupání je zdarma.
Vesnická hasičská nádrž.

Olšanský rybník je průtočný rybník na Olšanském potoce, levém přítoku Kunratického potoka, na okraji Prahy-Kunratic, nedaleko známého rybníku a koupaliště Šeberák. Severní a východní břeh rybníka je hranicí Šeberova. Rybník má rozlohu 4,4 ha Objem činí 69 000 m³, při maximální hladině pak 76 000 m³. Rybník je využíván k chovu ryb či rekreaci.
column14: Olšanský rybník je průtočný rybník na Olšanském potoce, levém přítoku Kunratického potoka, na okraji Prahy-Kunratic, nedaleko známého rybníku a koupaliště Šeberák. Větší rybník s nedostatečně udržovaným okolím. Vodní rostliny ve vodě u pláže komplikují přístup do vody.

Hrnčířský rybník je rybník u vesnice Hrnčíře spadající pod Šeberov. Spadá pod přírodní památku Hrnčířské louky, je její největší rybník. Má dva přítoky, z jihozápadu Kunratický potok a z jihu další potok, stejnětak má dva odtoky, které se ale spojují do Kunratického potoka. Po hrázi vede silnice (ulice) K Labeškám spojující Hrnčíře s Kunraticemi a Kunratickou spojkou. Ta je dlouhá přibližně 300 metrů a šířku má 13 m. Celková délka pobřeží je kolem 930 m.
Berounka
column14: Půjčovna kánoí s možností koupání. Celoroční místo pro koupaní otižilců zs spolku ŘOVSOŽ.

column14: Perfect swimming and picnic spot. But beware, parking wardens do come here. Do not park on yellow lines!

Steep white scree slopes plunge 500 metres into England's deepest lake, overlooked by Scafell Pike, its highest mountain. I like to swim across to the opposite shore, clamber around on the giant rocks then dive back in. After you've dried off on the quartz-sand beach, treat yourself to a pint at the Wasdale Head Inn.

The undisputed canyoning star of the Pyrenees (if not Europe), the Río is a dramatic river and gorge with miles of pools, chutes and waterfalls interspersed with great hiking. The steep cliffs above are dotted with cave chambers once inhabited by prehistoric man and now home to countless huge vultures. Start from the ancient fortress village of Alquézar, descend into the gorge and explore upstream.

Near the village of Ilay are a series of wonderful lakes. Relatively unknown and peaceful, these are superb for swimming. Lac d'Ilay is the largest and shallowest, the water is warm, and there is a grassy area that leads down to the beach. The early mornings here are particularly atmospheric, when great swathes of mist rise up over the lake. Nearby Lac de Narlay has a shoreside campsite and also a small cliff area for jumping and diving.

Some of the most spectacular river pools in France are in the mountains behind Nice. My favourite is the Estéron, which has sliced a white slot canyon with great marble pools through the centre of the mountains. There is a dramatic bridge, deep clear pools and many opportunities for swimming, including the deep mountain chasm itself. Aiglun is four miles west from the fortified village of Sigale.

Few places are as romantic as Lake Como, and beautiful, tiny Bellagio is as chic as it gets. Most visitors will pause at the cafés and boutiques that line the cobbled stairways, but wild swimmers should stride 20 minutes along Via Roma to the very tip of the peninsula and the old harbour. Here you will find views over the lake in all directions - and the perfect bay with walls from which to jump and dive.

column9: Great beach, lots of fun

column9: A beautiful alpine lake
Nice place with food, drinks, toilettes, camp
Rybník s vybudovanou houpackou
Pro hosty penzionu ale dá se domluvit

The Julian Alps offer top-class swimming, including the lovely-but-costly Lake Bled lido. However, travel down the road to Triglav National Park’s Lake Bohinj and discover wilder scenery for free. The Sava Bohinjka River provides a chilly thrill for flow-swimming fans.

Swim through several secret sea caves at this delightful Devonshire dipping spot, including one tide-swept tunnel hidden from lily-livered landlubbers. Wildlife along this part of the coast includes seals, dolphins and porpoises.

An urban oasis during the summer swelter, this 400m-long swimming canal in the fast-flowing river Limmat is a spot that attracts hundreds of swimmers. There’s a 2m diving board, plus a bar and beach volleyball fields.

The hike to the pools in this canyoning hotspot is demanding, but worth the effort. Swim in – and slide between – a series of pools fed by crystal-clear mountain water, and enjoy an infinity pool teetering on a waterfall edge.

Camp beneath mountains on the north shore of this stunning beach-lined lake, and slide into the embrace of its gin-clear water. Take a snorkel – there’s much to explore, including a rumoured submerged village.
Beautiful lake to spend some time sunbathing or go for a swim. Not so many people.
The hot springs of the Ötztal Valley are good for body and soul – and there is no better place to enjoy them than the exclusive Aqua Dome in Längenfeld.
The Aqua Nova is a spa and leisure centre in the Lechtal Valley, where families with children can splash around and relax.

The Tannheimer Tal Valley and its Schattwald forest enjoy many hours of sunshine, so it seems logical that it is home to a small lake, the Moorweiher Floschen, ideal for cooling off on a hot summer’s day.
The Frauensee (literally women's lake) is a small lake up to 40m deep in places. Contrary to what its name may suggest, it is open both men and women!
The "Waldbad Gieringer Weiher"" is a stunningly beautiful moorland lake situated in a forest just outside Giering in Reith bei Kitzbühel and surrounded by the mighty peaks of the Kaiser Mountains."
The charming "Moorstrandbad Kirchbichl"" is one of the oldest open-air swimming lakes in Tirol."

This charming lake perched on a plateau to the south of Innsbruck is popular with locals and visitors alike, who are drawn by the fabulous views, exceptionally clean water, large sunbathing lawns and shady trees.

May is normally a little too early in Tirol to start thinking about digging out the swimming trunks and heading for the nearest lake, but Lake Lauchsee near Fieberbrunn in the Pillerseetal Valley is a top tip for those who just can’t wait for summer to arrive.

Lake Pillersee near the village of St. Ulrich in the Kitzbühel Alps takes its name from the Pillerseetal Valley where it is located. This haven of peace and quiet is surrounded by beautiful mountains with many activities for all the family.
The Plansee in the district of Reutte is the second-largest natural lake in Tirol after the Achensee. Like a fjord, it lies between the forest-covered ridges of the Zwiesel and Spießberg mountains.
The small but perfectly formed Lake Reither See in the Alpbachtal Valley is a haven of peace and quiet popular with visitors of all ages.
From peace and quiet to fun and action, the "Badesee Ried"" swimming lake between Ried and Prutz in the Tiroler Oberland offers something for everyone on hot summer days."

Located at the entrance to the Zillertal Valley, the Badesee Schlitters is a beautiful swimming lake with spacious lawns for sunbathing, wooden walkways onto the water, plenty of alpine vegetation and warm temperatures in the summer months.
Trams is the name given to the plateau between Landeck and Zams. Here, surrounded by a small forest at the foot of the Venet mountain, lies the "Tramser Badeweiher""."
The Naturschutzgebiet Vilsalpsee nature reserve is home to two beautiful lakes: the Vilsalpsee and the Traualpsee.
Situated in a small valley at the foot of the Lienz Dolomites, Lake Tristacher See is one of the best-known and most popular lakes in East Tirol.
Great place for rest and relaxation. The water is pleasant and especially it is gradual. Great for kids.
Amazing place. Pool, lap pool, dive boards, splash pool, Mini golf, small zip line, trampolines, beach volleyball for adults and kids, ping pong, billiards!  Something for everyone!
Super swimming pool near Tachov. Admission 3 EUR, free parking. Food from 1 EUR.

Very enjoyable beach and area! Good for a lakewim and fun on the Wibbit for the kids. The different pools (3 total) are a great plus, but for me nothing beats swimming in the fresh water of the lake!

Amazingly beautiful place. Not a tough path. We parked at San  Martino 7 euro per day, then took bus to the start of the walking path. 2 euro  per person.

Nice little natural bath. Absolutely invites to relax. The wooden footbridge has become very beautiful. Everything was clean and tidy. Admission is completely ok. Unfortunately a little parking if you rely on the car. Nevertheless, clear recommendation for the great bathroom.
Beautiful part of river, beach access, very deep, clean water.

Good place for a swim or beach volleyball game during Summer. Also close to the lake itself and a good grill restaurant. Water is cold though, if one goes there with small kids, that might be too cold.

Wild canyon river with around 1 m of water to bath in (water level rises during rain). Water is a bit cloudy, but fresh and clean.

Wild river running through a long high karst cave tunnel. The river is usually shallow, but water level may rise during or after rain. Be careful about flash floods. Take a bath in an absolute darkness.
Shallow stream running through the campsite. Not really for swimming, but good enough to bath, refresh and wash yourself. Runs through the Glavoi campsite. Nevertheless the water is fresh and clean.
Wild karst canyon river Galbena emerges from a rock in a massive waterfall, which forms a small pool under itself. Water level rises during rain, so be careful for flash floods.

The karst river Galbena emerges upon surface in a small pond that overflows down into the canyon. Water is a bit cloudy, but good for bath and refreshment. Also the pond has and edge over which the water falls down into the canyon, so be careful about the stream.

Rybník s vodou přijatelnou pro koupání. Nejčistější voda je na jihovýchodním okraji u přítoků z lesních potůčků. Přístup po trouchnivějícím dřevěném molu - pozůstatku skautského tábora je trochu schovaný v rákosí. Příjezd autem po polních cestách je možný.
Koupat se ale dá i jinde - u chatek vedle hráze nebo v táboře Radost.

Titisee is the largest natural lake in Black Forest and one of the most popular attractions of the region.
There is a lot to see and do in the Lake Müritz region, including hiking or biking around the lake or swimming or boating in its calm waters.

Very nice swimming pool. Lake view is wonderful. Swimming pool area varied designed, well heated water. Giant slide, bubble beds, whirlpools, great toddler pool and terrific playground. Kiosk offers good selection and is organized.
Greatest lake ever. Largest lake in the Black Forest. You can swim, cycle, ferry, ride pedal boats, hiking and and and. Very nice. A must see!!!

One of the most incredible locations that I have ever visited. A photogenic / photographer's paradise. Every angle is pure bliss. Amazing scenery and very tranquil. There's a bunch of things to do all over and around the lake. From hiking, to swimming, boating, stand-up paddling... A great place to visit all year long.
Nice lake for swimming.

Lovely natural setting. Water is cool but lovely and refreshing. €4 euro adult entry but we were near closing so half price. Nice beer! New ownership, lovely manager. Worth a trip down for sure!

Nice natural bath, no entrance fee, snack available and only to be recommended. Hot water showers available for a small fee. Beautiful and spacious lawn. Various sports available.
Good for swimming, nice environment, the water is brown, but there are no algae. Sanitary facilities are also available, as well as a kiosk.

Great outdoor pool in Erbendorf. The area is older but lovingly maintained and extended. A toddler paddling pool, the large transition basin (about 50-80cm deep) with the super-wide double-wave slide and the deep swimming pool with diving tower are available. Everywhere free beach chairs and umbrellas, plus large meadow areas with lots of shade through old trees. At the end of a large sandbox for the youngest, in which also properly "egg lamp"" can be made. In addition small entrance fees and free to 6 years complete the great offer."
Beautiful mountain lake, but really cold, worth a visit.
Beautiful and peaceful. Great place for a walk, run or swim. Cold water.
Nice outdoor pool. Huge lawn with many shade places. Big trees. Mini golf course and playground for older and younger children with sun shade for shade.
The Inselbad is really great. Especially the toddlers area I find great and more than fair, that children only have to pay from the age of six.
Super beautiful lake. A big sandy beach. Parking is right in front of the entrance costs with entry 7 €. The lake is very clean.
Beautiful lake with crystal clear water. In good weather, the beaches are a bit crowded, but you can find a place with a bit of luck.

It is very clean, has a children's pool for the little ones, a slide, a 1 meter and a 3 meter tower in an extra basin. There is a kiosk, but of course it is a bit more expensive. Generally great swimming pool.
Nice lake, nice to linger, swim, play. There is even a fenced toddler area in the lake. Is also a good starting point for various hikes. As you say: small but nice.
Nice place to relax. Unfortunately, many people leave their garbage there.
A great place to walk, swim and relax.

Very nice bathroom with plenty of space, especially the outdoor pool. Friendly lifeguards and restaurant in the high prices, but the food was very good. For children is also much offered, especially the children's playground and the beach volleyball facility.
Perfect natural bath, clean soft water without chlorine! Very nice, relaxing atmosphere.
Very nice outdoor pool with stunning views of the surroundings!

Great location for fishing and taking pictures. Of course also suitable for swimming.
Beautiful lake with clear water, grassy beach and ample parking. Refreshments in basic form.

Great place good price for all day kids loved it and a little restaurant to eat at while the kids enjoy the pool.
One of the largest and most beautiful outdoor pools in Germany ... Wonderfully located in the forest with plenty of space for swimming and sunbathing.
Cold but beautiful nature lake. Outdoor swimming pool with bare nature crossed. Entrance price unbeatable.
Very nice pool! Great children's pool with lazy river, whirpool and two slides. Large lawn with deck chairs, very good and inexpensive food.
This is a unique place for swimming, sunbathing and dwelling on hot summer days. Huge area on the hillside of Stationsberg. I'm only missing the ropes of the swimming lanes.
Highly Recommended! Clean, not crowded, low prices, also at the kiosk and everything fresh made. Enough space and, if necessary, shade for everyone.
Nice small well-kept outdoor pool. Great what was made of it. Good food at reasonable prices.
Large and beautiful swimming pool.

The swimming pool is 15 minutes walk from the city. The water is currently a bit cold, but to swim in the evening perfect. From 5PM there is even an evening tariff (€ 2.50). There are also 5 volleyball fields and enough sunbathing area.
Very nice river pool with mature trees that gives beautiful shade.
Very nice outdoor pool with a 25-meter slide, a very short but steep and a very small slide for the little ones.
Great place with natural pool. Beautiful lawn and small kiosk. Jump system here. Clean and groomed.
Very nice swimming pool. Ideal for children. Nice tobogan.
The bathroom was already a bit old, but still great: great pool, slide, lots of space and a very good restaurant. And all at absolutely fair prices.
Very nice natural bath with spacious areas for swimming and fun for young and old.

column9: Very nice spa in the middle of the Alpes. If you enjoy sauna, this is definitely a good place to be. Saunas are clean and large, you can cool down in one of the pools/showers or jump into the lake (take the stairs or lift down). All pools have an incredible panorama view on the mountains.

A very nice swimming pool. The wave pool is great as well as the warm pool. The prices are also very good.
A real insider tip. Excellent food, nice and clean area, extra children's pool and diving tower.

Located 1 km from Dzitnup, the Samulá Cenote is a truly beautiful underground cavern.

The interior is lit by an orifice from above, where the roots hang from a tree. Visitors can admire its many fish, thanks to its clear waters.

The caretakers have laid several trails for visitors to walk along that lead to the entrance of the cenote and the craft stalls. Visitors can snorkel and swim here. You can rent equipment if you haven´t brought any with you.
[http://mundomaya.travel/en/naturaleza/espacios-naturales/item/cenote-samula.html]

column9: Tham Kong Lo or Kong Lor Cave is the limestone cave in Phu Hin Bun National Park, in Khammouane Province, Laos. It is located roughly 130 kilometres (81 mi) north of Thakhek, on the Nam Hin Bun River, which flows into the cave. Inside the cave is a pool which glows a bright emerald colour which locals hold as sacred, believing it to reflect the skin of the Hindi god Indra.

There are three waterfalls in this village: Tad Suong, Tad Lo and Tad Hang. If you want to take a quick swim Tad Hang is the best bet for you. The water is not too rough as long as you stay away from the falls themselves. Fishing is very common and though the water is not crystal clear, it is not unhealthy.

Tad E-Tu is set in a picturesque basin filled with wild butterflies and dragonflies.  Flowing from the Vang Ngao River, the waterfall is accessed via steep steps along the side of a gorge. Swimming is possible at Tad E-Tu but the force of the water during rainy season means swimming here is not a good idea.
